  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Hodgkin's lymphoma is notable for the frequency with which it presents with pruritus, occurring in up to 30% of patients. The pruritus of lymphoma often precedes the clinical diagnosis by months or, rarely, years. Pruritus as a paraneoplastic phenomenon is seen in several malignancies, but Hodgkin's lymphoma is the prototype. The pruritus is thought to be mediated by cytokines released from the malignant cells. Treatment of the underlying malignancy usually leads to resolution of the pruritus.",
