  "source": "Obstentrics_Williams_textbook_data.txt: Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy (ICP) is characterized by pruritus without a rash, typically beginning in the third trimester. The pruritus characteristically affects the palms and soles and worsens at night. Laboratory findings include elevated serum bile acids (>10 μmol/L), which is the most sensitive and specific test, and mild elevations in aminotransferases. Bilirubin levels are usually normal or slightly elevated (usually <6 mg/dL). ICP increases the risk of adverse fetal outcomes, including preterm birth, meconium-stained amniotic fluid, and intrauterine fetal demise. The principal aim of management is to alleviate maternal symptoms and reduce perinatal morbidity and mortality. Ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA) is the first-line treatment. Delivery timing is usually recommended between 36 and 38 weeks, depending on the severity of the disease and previous obstetric history.",
