  "source": "Pathology_Robbins_textbook_data.txt: Allergic contact dermatitis is a type IV hypersensitivity reaction that requires prior sensitization to an allergen. Common allergens include metals (nickel, gold), topical antibiotics (neomycin), rubber compounds, dyes, cosmetics, and plant resins (e.g., poison ivy). The reaction is characterized by erythema, vesiculation, and pruritus. The distribution of lesions is limited to the site of contact with the allergen, which may provide a clue to the inciting agent. The reaction typically occurs 24-72 hours after antigen exposure. Diagnosis is confirmed by patch testing, which involves the application of small amounts of potential allergens to the skin and assessing for a reaction.",
