  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Dermographism (\"writing on the skin\") is the most common physical urticaria, affecting about 2-5% of the population. Firm stroking of the skin produces an initial red line (capillary dilatation), followed by a wheal and flare from local mast cell degranulation. Dermographism can be diagnosed by drawing a tongue blade across the skin or using a calibrated instrument (dermographometer) that applies a predefined pressure to the skin. A positive test is characterized by the appearance of a linear wheal at the site of the stroke. Symptoms include pruritus and burning at sites of pressure or friction from clothing or activity. Lesions are typically linear or geometric and usually resolve within 1 hour.",
