  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: In elderly patients with generalized pruritus without a primary dermatologic disorder, a focused work-up should include a complete blood count with differential, metabolic panel (including renal and liver function tests), and thyroid function tests. Renal dysfunction is a common cause of pruritus in the elderly, particularly those with diabetes or hypertension, due to the accumulation of uremic toxins. Chronic kidney disease may be asymptomatic in its early stages, with pruritus developing as the disease progresses. Approximately 40% of patients with advanced CKD experience pruritus. In elderly patients with xerosis and pruritus, renal function should be assessed even in the absence of other uremic symptoms.",
