  "source": "Pharmacology_Katzung_textbook_data.txt: Opioid-induced pruritus is a common side effect of opioid analgesics, occurring in up to 10% of patients taking these medications. Tramadol, as a weak μ-opioid receptor agonist and serotonin/norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor, can cause pruritus, though less frequently than pure μ-agonists like morphine. Opioids induce pruritus through central and peripheral mechanisms, including μ-receptor-mediated mast cell degranulation with histamine release, and alteration of itch processing in the central nervous system. The pruritus is often generalized and may be worse at night. Management includes opioid dose reduction, rotation to an alternative opioid, or addition of an opioid antagonist like naloxone at low doses that do not compromise analgesia. A drug challenge test, where the medication is withdrawn and then reintroduced while monitoring for symptom recurrence, can confirm the diagnosis.",
