  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP) occurs in patients without clinically apparent lung disease, typically in tall, thin males between the ages of 10 and 30 years. Smoking increases the risk of PSP by up to 20-fold in a dose-dependent manner. The pathophysiology involves rupture of subpleural blebs or bullae, which are small air-filled sacs that develop in the lung apex. Patients with PSP typically present with the sudden onset of ipsilateral chest pain and dyspnea. The pain is sharp, may be severe, and is exacerbated by breathing. Physical examination may reveal diminished breath sounds, decreased tactile fremitus, hyperresonance to percussion, and decreased chest wall excursion on the affected side. Diagnosis is confirmed by chest radiography, which demonstrates a visible visceral pleural line separated from the parietal pleura by a lucent space devoid of lung markings.",
