  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) is defined as pneumonia that is acquired outside of the hospital or healthcare setting. Common bacterial pathogens include Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, atypical bacteria (Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Chlamydia pneumoniae, Legionella spp.), and viral pathogens. Clinical manifestations include cough, sputum production, dyspnea, pleuritic chest pain, and constitutional symptoms such as fever, fatigue, and myalgias. Physical examination may reveal tachypnea, tachycardia, and abnormal lung findings (crackles, bronchial breath sounds, egophony). Diagnosis is confirmed by chest radiography showing pulmonary infiltrates. Initial empiric antibiotic therapy is guided by the severity of illness, comorbidities, and local resistance patterns. For hospitalized patients not requiring ICU admission, recommended regimens include a respiratory fluoroquinolone (e.g., levofloxacin) or a combination of a β-lactam (e.g., ceftriaxone) plus a macrolide (e.g., azithromycin).",
