  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Anticoagulation is the mainstay of therapy for acute pulmonary embolism (PE). Options include unfractionated heparin (UFH), low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH), fondaparinux, and direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs). Intravenous UFH is preferred for patients with hemodynamic instability, severe renal insufficiency, or those who may require thrombolysis, embolectomy, or have a high bleeding risk. UFH is administered as an initial bolus followed by a continuous infusion, adjusted to maintain the aPTT at 1.5-2.5 times control. Advantages of UFH include its short half-life and complete reversibility with protamine sulfate. For intermediate-risk PE (right ventricular dysfunction or myocardial necrosis without hypotension), standard anticoagulation is recommended, with close monitoring and consideration of rescue thrombolysis if clinical deterioration occurs. Thrombolytic therapy is recommended for high-risk PE (with hypotension or shock) but carries a significant risk of major bleeding, including intracranial hemorrhage.",
