  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Exercise stress testing is the most commonly used noninvasive test for evaluation of patients with suspected coronary artery disease. It is particularly useful in patients with intermediate pretest probability of coronary artery disease based on age, sex, and symptoms. The standard exercise stress test involves continuous ECG monitoring during progressively increasing exercise loads, typically using a treadmill or bicycle ergometer. The test assesses exercise capacity, blood pressure and heart rate response, development of symptoms, and ECG changes. A positive test is characterized by horizontal or downsloping ST-segment depression ≥1 mm measured 80 ms after the J point, developing during exercise or in recovery. Exercise stress testing is most suitable for patients with a normal resting ECG who are able to exercise and have no contraindications such as unstable angina, decompensated heart failure, life-threatening arrhythmias, or severe aortic stenosis.",
  "category": "Cardiology"
