  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is characterized by troublesome symptoms or complications resulting from the reflux of gastric contents into the esophagus or beyond. The most common symptoms are heartburn and regurgitation. Heartburn is characterized by a retrosternal burning sensation that may radiate to the throat or neck and is often exacerbated by meals, lying down, or bending over. Regurgitation is the perception of refluxed gastric contents in the mouth or hypopharynx. Atypical or extraesophageal manifestations of GERD include chest pain, dysphagia, globus sensation, asthma, chronic cough, hoarseness, and dental erosions. Risk factors for GERD include foods that may trigger reflux (coffee, chocolate, alcohol, fatty foods, spicy foods), obesity, pregnancy, smoking, and certain medications (calcium channel blockers, nitrates, anticholinergics, benzodiazepines).",
