  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Bronchiectasis is defined as an irreversible dilatation of bronchi with destruction of the elastic and muscular components of the bronchial walls. It is characterized by chronic cough with mucopurulent sputum production, recurrent respiratory infections, and hemoptysis. Physical examination may reveal crackles, rhonchi, or clubbing. The diagnosis is best established by high-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) of the chest, which shows bronchial dilatation (bronchial lumen diameter greater than accompanying pulmonary artery, 'signet ring sign'), lack of bronchial tapering, bronchial wall thickening, and mucus plugging. Common etiologies include post-infectious (bacterial, tuberculous), primary ciliary dyskinesia, allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, immunodeficiency states, and cystic fibrosis. Sputum cultures often reveal potentially pathogenic organisms, most commonly Haemophilus influenzae, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Streptococcus pneumoniae. Management includes bronchial hygiene measures, antimicrobials for exacerbations, and surgical resection in localized disease with significant symptoms.",
