  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Mitral stenosis is characterized by obstruction to left ventricular filling due to narrowing of the mitral valve orifice. Rheumatic fever remains the predominant cause worldwide, though its incidence has declined in developed countries. The normal mitral valve area is 4-6 cm²; symptoms develop when the area decreases to <2.5 cm². Clinical manifestations include dyspnea on exertion, fatigue, palpitations, and hemoptysis. Hemoptysis occurs in 10-15% of patients due to rupture of pulmonary-bronchial venous connections and is rarely massive. Physical examination reveals a diastolic rumbling murmur, an opening snap, and signs of pulmonary congestion. Electrocardiography may show left atrial enlargement and atrial fibrillation. Echocardiography is the diagnostic gold standard, demonstrating valve thickening, calcification, reduced leaflet motion, and left atrial enlargement. Treatment includes diuretics for symptom relief, beta-blockers or calcium channel blockers for rate control in atrial fibrillation, anticoagulation to prevent thromboembolism, and percutaneous balloon mitral valvuloplasty or surgical valve replacement for severe symptomatic stenosis.",
