  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Lung cancer is the leading cause of cancer-related mortality worldwide, with cigarette smoking being the primary risk factor. Clinical manifestations depend on the location and size of the tumor and can include cough, hemoptysis, dyspnea, chest pain, and constitutional symptoms such as weight loss and fatigue. Hemoptysis occurs in approximately 20-30% of patients with lung cancer. Superior sulcus tumors (Pancoast tumors) may cause shoulder pain and Horner's syndrome due to invasion of the brachial plexus and sympathetic chain. Radiographic findings typically include a solitary pulmonary nodule or mass, often with irregular borders, and may be accompanied by hilar or mediastinal lymphadenopathy. Central tumors are more likely to cause hemoptysis due to erosion into blood vessels. The diagnosis is established by histologic or cytologic examination of tumor tissue, obtained by bronchoscopy, CT-guided needle biopsy, or surgical procedures. Treatment depends on the cell type, disease stage, and patient's performance status, with options including surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and targeted therapy.",
