  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Bronchial carcinoid tumors are neuroendocrine neoplasms that account for 1-2% of all lung tumors. They occur most commonly in the third and fourth decades of life and show no gender predilection. Approximately 80% of bronchial carcinoids are classified as typical carcinoids, which are low-grade malignancies with excellent prognosis, while the remaining 20% are atypical carcinoids with more aggressive behavior. Most bronchial carcinoids (70%) occur in the main, lobar, or segmental bronchi, and the remainder develop in the peripheral lung. Symptoms result from bronchial obstruction (cough, wheeze, recurrent pneumonia) or, less commonly, from hormone production (carcinoid syndrome, Cushing's syndrome). Hemoptysis occurs in approximately 20-30% of patients due to the highly vascular nature of these tumors. Bronchoscopy typically reveals a smooth, round, pink or reddish endobronchial lesion that bleeds easily with manipulation. CT imaging shows a well-circumscribed nodule, often with punctate calcifications, and may also demonstrate post-obstructive atelectasis or pneumonia. Treatment for localized disease is primarily surgical resection, with excellent long-term survival rates (>90% at 5 years for typical carcinoids).",
