  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - The pulmonary-renal syndrome is defined by the combination of diffuse alveolar hemorrhage (DAH) and glomerulonephritis. This syndrome may be caused by a variety of disorders, including ANCA-associated vasculitis (AAV), anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) disease, immune complex-mediated diseases such as systemic lupus erythematosus, and rarely, drug-induced vasculitis. Microscopic polyangiitis (MPA) is one of the most common causes of pulmonary-renal syndrome, characterized by necrotizing small-vessel vasculitis with few or no immune deposits, and is strongly associated with perinuclear ANCA (p-ANCA) directed against myeloperoxidase (MPO). Clinical manifestations include constitutional symptoms (fever, weight loss, fatigue), pulmonary involvement (dyspnea, cough, hemoptysis), and renal disease (hematuria, proteinuria, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis). The diagnosis of AAV relies on a combination of clinical features, serologic testing for ANCA, and histopathologic findings. Serologic testing should include ANA, ANCA with immunofluorescence pattern (cytoplasmic or perinuclear) and ELISA for specific antigens (PR3 and MPO), and anti-GBM antibodies. Tissue diagnosis is often necessary, with renal biopsy generally preferred over lung biopsy due to higher diagnostic yield and lower risk. Treatment includes high-dose corticosteroids and cyclophosphamide or rituximab for remission induction.",
