  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Cardiogenic pulmonary edema results from elevated pulmonary venous pressure due to left heart failure, leading to transudation of fluid into the pulmonary interstitium and alveoli. Common causes include acute coronary syndromes, decompensated heart failure, valvular heart disease, and hypertensive emergencies. Clinical manifestations include dyspnea, orthopnea, tachypnea, tachycardia, rales on auscultation, and occasionally pink frothy sputum, which represents a mixture of edema fluid and small amounts of blood from ruptured capillaries. The diagnosis is based on clinical presentation, chest radiography showing interstitial edema, vascular redistribution, and pleural effusions, and elevated natriuretic peptide levels (BNP or NT-proBNP). Echocardiography helps assess left ventricular function, valvular abnormalities, and diastolic dysfunction. Management includes positioning the patient upright to decrease venous return, oxygen supplementation to correct hypoxemia, and diuretics (intravenous furosemide) to reduce preload. In severe cases, non-invasive positive pressure ventilation may be beneficial. Vasodilators such as nitroglycerin reduce preload and afterload, improving cardiac output. Severe refractory cases may require inotropic support or mechanical circulatory assistance. The underlying cause (e.g., ischemia, arrhythmia, valvular disease) should be identified and treated concurrently.",
