  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - The initial management of massive hemoptysis focuses on maintaining airway patency, ensuring adequate oxygenation and ventilation, and restoring hemodynamic stability. Patients should be positioned with the bleeding lung in the dependent position to prevent aspiration of blood into the unaffected lung. Intubation is often necessary for airway protection and may be performed with a single-lumen endotracheal tube, though selective intubation of the main bronchus of the non-bleeding lung can be considered in extreme cases. Double-lumen endotracheal tubes allow isolation of the bleeding lung but are technically more difficult to place, especially in emergency situations. After airway stabilization, efforts should be made to localize the source of bleeding. Chest radiography may reveal infiltrates or cavitary lesions, but may not accurately identify the bleeding site if there is aspiration of blood into both lungs. Rigid or flexible bronchoscopy can help locate the bleeding source and provide therapeutic interventions such as local instillation of epinephrine, cold saline lavage, or endobronchial blockade using a Fogarty catheter. Blood volume should be restored with intravenous fluids and blood products as needed. Correction of coagulopathy is essential, using fresh frozen plasma, platelets, or specific factor replacement as indicated. Definitive management typically involves bronchial artery embolization, though surgery may be necessary for localized disease when embolization fails or is unavailable.",
