  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Diabetes mellitus (DM) frequently presents with the classic triad of polyuria, polydipsia, and weight loss. The polyuria in diabetes mellitus is osmotic in nature, resulting from filtered glucose exceeding the renal threshold (approximately 180 mg/dL in most individuals), leading to glucosuria. This osmotic load carries water with it, increasing urine output. Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) accounts for 90-95% of diabetes cases and is characterized by insulin resistance and relative insulin deficiency. Initial management of newly diagnosed T2DM depends on the severity of hyperglycemia, presence of symptoms, and comorbidities. For most patients with an HbA1c less than 9%, initial management includes lifestyle modifications (diet, exercise, weight loss) and metformin, unless contraindicated. Metformin is recommended as first-line therapy due to its efficacy, safety profile, weight neutrality or modest weight loss effect, extensive clinical experience, and low cost. It primarily reduces hepatic glucose production and improves insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues. Common side effects include gastrointestinal symptoms (diarrhea, nausea, abdominal discomfort), which can be minimized by starting with a low dose and gradually titrating upward, and taking the medication with meals. Metformin is contraindicated in patients with significant renal impairment (eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73 m²), severe hepatic disease, or conditions predisposing to lactic acidosis. For patients with more severe hyperglycemia (HbA1c ≥9%) but without symptoms of metabolic decompensation (polyuria, polydipsia, weight loss), dual therapy with metformin plus another agent (such as a DPP-4 inhibitor, SGLT2 inhibitor, GLP-1 receptor agonist, sulfonylurea, thiazolidinedione, or basal insulin) may be initiated. In patients presenting with significant hyperglycemia (blood glucose >300-350 mg/dL, HbA1c >10-12%) and symptoms of polyuria, polydipsia, and weight loss, insulin therapy (with or without metformin) is often required initially. Once glycemic control is achieved, insulin may be tapered and potentially discontinued if beta cell function is preserved. Patients with severe metabolic decompensation (diabetic ketoacidosis or hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state) require immediate treatment with intravenous fluids, electrolyte replacement, and insulin therapy. Monitoring and follow-up care should include education about self-management, glucose monitoring, recognition of hypoglycemia, and regular assessment for complications. HbA1c should be measured every 3-6 months, with a general target of <7% for most patients, though individualization based on age, comorbidities, and hypoglycemia risk is essential.",
  "category": "Endocrinology"
},

