  "source": "Psichiatry_DSM-5_textbook_data.txt: 'Polydipsia (excessive water intake) can occur in patients with psychotic disorders, particularly schizophrenia, and may lead to water intoxication with hyponatremia. This condition, known as psychogenic polydipsia or primary polydipsia, is characterized by excessive fluid intake without physiological stimulus to drink. Management involves behavioral modification strategies including gradual reduction of fluid intake, maintaining a fluid intake diary, and regular monitoring of body weight and serum sodium levels. Antipsychotic medications, particularly clozapine, have been associated with both causing and ameliorating polydipsia in different individuals.'",
