  "source": "urology_Adams_textbook_data.txt: Management of hypercalciuria includes both dietary and pharmacological approaches. Increased fluid intake to achieve urine output of 2-2.5 L/day is essential to dilute calcium concentration. Dietary sodium restriction to <2300 mg/day significantly reduces urinary calcium excretion, as sodium and calcium reabsorption in the proximal tubule are linked. Thiazide diuretics (e.g., hydrochlorothiazide 25-50 mg/day) are the pharmacological cornerstone of hypercalciuria management, decreasing urinary calcium excretion by enhancing calcium reabsorption in the distal tubule. This approach reduces stone recurrence by 50-75% in patients with hypercalciuria and recurrent calcium stones.",
