  "source": "Pharmacology_Katzung_textbook_data.txt: Sympathomimetic agents like pseudoephedrine can cause significant cardiovascular adverse effects including palpitations, tachycardia, and elevated blood pressure. These effects are mediated through both direct stimulation of β1-adrenergic receptors in the heart and indirect release of norepinephrine from sympathetic nerve terminals. First-generation antihistamines such as diphenhydramine possess significant anticholinergic properties that can lead to tachycardia through vagal inhibition. The combination of sympathomimetic decongestants and anticholinergic antihistamines may have synergistic effects on heart rate. Management of drug-induced palpitations primarily involves discontinuation of the offending agent(s), with complete resolution typically occurring within days. Patients with underlying anxiety disorders may be particularly sensitive to the sympathomimetic effects of these medications and experience heightened awareness of normal or slightly increased heart rates.",
