  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Hypokalemia-induced arrhythmias represent a major clinical concern, as potassium plays a critical role in maintaining myocardial cell electrical stability. ECG manifestations of hypokalemia include ST-segment depression, T-wave flattening, prominent U waves, QT interval prolongation, and increased amplitude of P waves. Severe hypokalemia (<2.7 mEq/L) can precipitate premature atrial and ventricular contractions, ventricular tachyarrhythmias, and conduction abnormalities. Management principles include: 1) Correction of underlying causes (discontinuation of offending medications such as diuretics or laxatives); 2) Oral potassium supplementation (typically KCl 40-80 mEq/day for mild-moderate deficiency) with higher doses for severe deficiency; 3) Correction of coexisting magnesium deficiency, which is essential for potassium repletion; and 4) Serial monitoring of serum electrolytes until normalized.",
