  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Pulmonary embolism (PE) should be considered in any patient with unexplained dyspnea, tachypnea, or chest pain, especially in those with risk factors for venous thromboembolism. Tachycardia is present in >40% of patients with PE and represents a compensatory mechanism for reduced cardiac output due to increased pulmonary vascular resistance and right ventricular strain. ECG findings may include sinus tachycardia, right bundle branch block, right axis deviation, and T-wave inversions in leads V1-V4 (reflecting right ventricular strain), though these changes are neither sensitive nor specific. Arterial blood gas typically shows hypoxemia, hypocapnia, and respiratory alkalosis. The combination of clinical presentation, elevated D-dimer (>500 ng/mL), and imaging findings establishes the diagnosis. Major risk factors include recent surgery, malignancy, prolonged immobilization, pregnancy or postpartum state, estrogen therapy, and known thrombophilia. Treatment involves anticoagulation, with thrombolytic therapy reserved for hemodynamically unstable patients.",
