  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Hereditary angioedema (HAE) acute attacks require prompt treatment, especially for laryngeal edema which can be life-threatening. First-line therapy for acute HAE attacks is C1 inhibitor concentrate (pdC1INH), which directly replaces the deficient protein. It is administered intravenously at 20 units/kg and typically produces improvement within 30-60 minutes. Alternative treatments include: icatibant (a bradykinin B2 receptor antagonist, 30mg subcutaneously) and ecallantide (a kallikrein inhibitor, 30mg subcutaneously). These agents specifically target the bradykinin pathway, which distinguishes HAE management from histamine-mediated angioedema treatments. Importantly, traditional treatments for allergic angioedema (antihistamines, corticosteroids, epinephrine) are ineffective in HAE. Fresh frozen plasma can be used when first-line therapies are unavailable, though it theoretically could exacerbate symptoms by providing additional substrate for the contact system.",
