  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor-induced angioedema represents a potentially life-threatening adverse reaction occurring in approximately 0.1-0.7% of patients taking these medications. The mechanism involves inhibition of bradykinin degradation, leading to its accumulation and consequent vasodilation and increased vascular permeability. Management of acute ACE inhibitor-induced angioedema focuses on immediate discontinuation of the offending drug and airway assessment. Patients with progressive upper airway edema require close monitoring for potential airway compromise, with preparation for endotracheal intubation or cricothyroidotomy if necessary. Standard treatments for histamine-mediated angioedema (antihistamines, corticosteroids, epinephrine) have limited efficacy but are often administered due to diagnostic uncertainty or inability to rule out allergic components. Bradykinin-targeted therapies (icatibant, C1-INH concentrate) have shown promise in case reports and small trials but are not FDA-approved for this indication. Following resolution, ACE inhibitors should be permanently avoided. Angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) can cause similar reactions in about 10% of patients with ACE inhibitor-induced angioedema, so caution is warranted when considering them as alternatives.",
