  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Approximately 30-40% of patients with chronic spontaneous urticaria (CSU) have an autoimmune etiology. Two major autoimmune mechanisms have been identified: (1) IgG autoantibodies against the high-affinity IgE receptor (FcεRI) or against IgE itself, which can activate mast cells and basophils; and (2) association with other autoimmune diseases, particularly autoimmune thyroid disease. Patients with CSU should be evaluated for thyroid dysfunction and autoimmunity, especially when clinical features suggest hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism. The prevalence of thyroid autoantibodies in CSU patients ranges from 10-30%, significantly higher than in the general population. Thyroid function tests (TSH, free T4) and thyroid autoantibodies (anti-thyroid peroxidase, anti-thyroglobulin) should be measured in patients with persistent CSU, particularly those with symptoms or signs of thyroid disease. Correction of thyroid dysfunction can lead to improvement or resolution of urticaria in some patients. The autologous serum skin test (ASST), which involves intradermal injection of the patient's own serum, can identify autoimmune urticaria, with a positive reaction suggesting the presence of circulating histamine-releasing factors, including autoantibodies.",
