  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Patient education is a cornerstone of hereditary angioedema (HAE) management. Patients should be informed about triggers to avoid, including: 1) Mechanical trauma, particularly dental and surgical procedures, which require prophylactic treatment; 2) ACE inhibitors, which inhibit bradykinin degradation and can precipitate or worsen attacks; 3) Estrogen-containing medications (oral contraceptives, hormone replacement therapy), which can increase attack frequency. Patients should be advised to carry appropriate medication for on-demand treatment and wear medical identification jewelry. Family members should be screened given the autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. Genetic counseling should be offered, explaining the 50% risk of transmission to offspring. HAE differs fundamentally from histamine-mediated angioedema, so patients should understand that antihistamines, epinephrine, and corticosteroids are ineffective for their condition. Long-term prophylaxis options, including C1 inhibitor concentrates, lanadelumab (kallikrein inhibitor), or attenuated androgens, should be discussed with patients experiencing frequent or severe attacks.",
