  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: 'Prolactinomas are the most common functioning pituitary adenomas. They account for about 30% of all pituitary adenomas. Patients with prolactinomas may present with amenorrhea, galactorrhea, and infertility in women. The excess prolactin secretion inhibits GnRH pulsatility and can lead to hypogonadism. Visual field defects may occur if the tumor is large enough to compress the optic chiasm. MRI typically reveals a hypoenhancing pituitary mass. Treatment with dopamine agonists such as cabergoline or bromocriptine is usually effective in normalizing prolactin levels and reducing tumor size.'",
