  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is the study of choice for the detection of disk disease. It is indicated in patients with severe or persistent symptoms, especially if surgery is being considered. MRI can detect disk protrusion, disk desiccation, annular tears, spinal stenosis, and other structural abnormalities. The diagnostic accuracy of MRI for disk disease is high, with a sensitivity of 83-96% and specificity of 68-75%. Both false-positive and false-negative findings are common; abnormalities on MRI, including disk protrusion, are present in many asymptomatic adults, especially those over age 40. Therefore, the clinical presentation should be the primary basis for diagnosis, with MRI serving to confirm a clinical impression. MRI is particularly valuable in evaluating patients with clinical evidence of nerve root compression who may benefit from surgical intervention.",
