  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Psoriatic arthritis (PsA) is an inflammatory arthritis associated with psoriasis, classified as a seronegative spondyloarthropathy. Approximately 15-30% of patients with PsA develop spinal involvement, characterized by inflammatory back pain, sacroiliitis, and sometimes axial disease resembling ankylosing spondylitis. Distinctive clinical features include psoriatic skin lesions (typically on elbows, knees, scalp, and intergluteal cleft), nail changes (pitting, onycholysis, hyperkeratosis), dactylitis (sausage-shaped swelling of fingers or toes), enthesitis (inflammation at tendon, ligament, or joint capsule insertions), and extra-articular manifestations such as uveitis. The disease affects men and women equally, typically presenting in the third to fifth decades. Family history is often positive, with HLA-B27 positivity more common than in the general population, though less frequent than in ankylosing spondylitis. Inflammatory back pain in PsA is characterized by insidious onset, improvement with exercise, worsening with rest, and morning stiffness lasting more than 30 minutes. Radiographic findings in the spine may include asymmetric sacroiliitis, non-marginal syndesmophytes, and asymmetric paravertebral ossification.",
