  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Hepatitis A virus (HAV) is transmitted by the fecal-oral route, and infection is facilitated by close personal contact and poor sanitation. Common source outbreaks may be traced to contaminated food, water, or shellfish. The incubation period averages 30 days (range 15–49 days). HAV replicates in the liver, reaches the liver via the portal vein, is shed into the bile and excreted in feces. Peak infectivity occurs during the 2-week period before the onset of jaundice. Virus is no longer detected in the stools after the first week of jaundice. Therefore, isolation of patients (beyond the usual precautions for patients with diarrhea) is not necessary after the first week of jaundice.",
