  "source": "Pathology_Robbins_textbook_data.txt - Hemolytic anemias are a diverse group of disorders characterized by shortened red cell survival. Hemolysis can result from intrinsic red cell defects, extrinsic factors that injure normal red cells, or a combination of these causes. Manifestations include jaundice (due to increased bilirubin from breakdown of hemoglobin), reticulocytosis, and, in severe cases, hemoglobinemia, hemoglobinuria, and hemosiderinuria. The diagnosis of hemolysis is supported by laboratory findings showing decreased haptoglobin, increased indirect bilirubin, elevated lactate dehydrogenase, and reticulocytosis. Examination of the peripheral blood smear may reveal red cell fragments, parasitized red cells, or abnormal red cell morphology indicative of the underlying cause.",
