  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Wilson's disease is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in ATP7B, a copper-transporting ATPase. The disease is characterized by excessive deposition of copper in the liver, brain, and other tissues. The major diagnostic findings include the presence of Kayser-Fleischer rings in the cornea, low serum ceruloplasmin levels (<20 mg/dL), elevated 24-hour urinary copper excretion (>100 μg/24 h), and elevated hepatic copper concentration (>250 μg/g dry weight) on liver biopsy. Neurologic manifestations include tremor, dysarthria, dystonia, and psychiatric disturbances. Early diagnosis and treatment with chelating agents (D-penicillamine, trientine) or zinc can prevent progression of liver and neurologic disease.",
