  "source": "Surgery_Schwartz_textbook_data.txt - Vascular complications after liver transplantation, particularly hepatic artery thrombosis (HAT), are serious events that can lead to graft failure and patient mortality. HAT occurs in 3-9% of adult liver transplant recipients and up to 15% of pediatric recipients. Early diagnosis is critical as emergency revascularization or retransplantation may be necessary. Doppler ultrasonography is the first-line imaging modality for suspected vascular complications due to its noninvasiveness, availability, and high sensitivity. It can detect abnormalities in hepatic arterial, portal venous, and hepatic venous flow. In the setting of HAT, patients typically present with fever, elevated liver enzymes, and biliary complications due to ischemia of the biliary epithelium, which receives its blood supply predominantly from the hepatic artery. The absence of arterial flow on Doppler ultrasonography is highly suggestive of HAT and should prompt immediate angiographic confirmation and intervention. Other causes of early graft dysfunction include acute cellular rejection, primary nonfunction, biliary complications, and infections (particularly cytomegalovirus).",
